@node INSTALL "How to install the files"
@prev AUTHOR
Simply copy the file `gmake' to somewhere in your path, most likely C:
@next USAGE
@endnode
@node USAGE "How to use the package"
@prev INSTALL
The user must create a GMakeFile which contains the names and information of the files to compile. These files that are compiled need make no mention of any amigaguide specific text.

To compile simply enter `gmake' on the command line.

Note: gmake understands 2 arguments either the name of the gmakefile or DEBUG. DEBUG requires KCON to be installed, KCON is © by David Larsson and provides history usage on a con: window.
@next PAGE1
@endnode
@node PAGE1 "The format of the GMakeFile"
@prev USAGE
The make file comprises of the format:

section_type:	file_name

For example:

guide:          AmigaGuideCompiler.guide
premain:        premain
postmain:       postmain
author:         me
disclaimer:     disc
about:          about
Usage:          usage


The guide is the output guide file, this *MUST* be mentioned.

PreMain and PostMain go before and after the contents on the main page.

Other standard sections and the order in which the appear are:

     Preface Disclaimer About Author Install Usage Bugs History


To include a non standard section add to the gmakefile:

page:		filename
		title of additional page

See the example within the package for more details.
@endnode
@node PAGE2 "The C source"
@prev PAGE1
The C source is included with this archive:

	debug.c  extra.c  file.c  main.c  str.c  type.c
	debug.h  info.h  main.h  standard.h   DMakefile

It can be compiled using DICE, but is probably easy to convert (the only amiga specifics are the arg inputs).

@endnode
